Yeah, I wanted to
touch on that.

00:31:40.580 --> 00:31:43.240
I come from a tiny little town
in North Carolina where

00:31:43.240 --> 00:31:45.020
bluegrass is the big thing.

00:31:45.020 --> 00:31:47.962
So where did you get your
bluegrass influence from?

00:31:47.962 --> 00:31:49.590
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Well,
I've heard some.

00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:51.920
Mostly, I think, in films.

00:31:51.920 --> 00:31:53.640
Maybe a few recordings
in the past.

00:31:53.640 --> 00:31:55.820
I've always been attracted
to it.

00:31:55.820 --> 00:31:58.180
We were in Ireland about three
years ago, and we played in a

00:31:58.180 --> 00:32:00.830
little town called Limerick.

00:32:00.830 --> 00:32:02.890
And they were having
a reception for me.

00:32:02.890 --> 00:32:05.280
So I'm supposed to walk in and
shake hands with all these

00:32:05.280 --> 00:32:07.220
guests, have my picture taken,
sign autographs,

00:32:07.220 --> 00:32:08.430
and stuff like that.

00:32:08.430 --> 00:32:11.630
And when I walked through the
door, there was a band playing

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:12.410
in the corner.

00:32:12.410 --> 00:32:15.310
And they were playing
genuine Irish music.

00:32:15.310 --> 00:32:18.690
I mean, the old traditional
stuff with the pipes, and the

00:32:18.690 --> 00:32:21.420
violin, the fiddle, and all that
kind of stuff, which is

00:32:21.420 --> 00:32:24.290
where our bluegrass
music comes.

00:32:24.290 --> 00:32:26.030
So I, sort of, gravitated
over there.

00:32:26.030 --> 00:32:28.010
Set in a chair and just hung
out with the band while all

00:32:28.010 --> 00:32:29.830
these people are waiting for
me to have my picture taken

00:32:29.830 --> 00:32:30.560
with them and stuff like that.

00:32:30.560 --> 00:32:32.250
And I completely ignored them.

00:32:32.250 --> 00:32:35.950
I couldn't help myself because
the music was so inviting.

00:32:35.950 --> 00:32:37.990
And it really pulled me
into their center.

00:32:37.990 --> 00:32:39.680
I just was stuck there.

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:41.990
I set down and I could not
believe what I was hearing

00:32:41.990 --> 00:32:43.760
because it was such
beautiful music.

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:51.570
I love the plain, simple rhythms
of the American heart.

00:32:51.570 --> 00:32:52.550
I love jazz.

00:32:52.550 --> 00:32:53.310
I love Bluegrass.

00:32:53.310 --> 00:32:57.550
Anything that's come out of
the soil, even though

00:32:57.550 --> 00:32:59.820
Bluegrass really is
from Ireland.

00:32:59.820 --> 00:33:00.080
[IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:00.080 --> 00:33:03.520
And I tried so hard to talk
like an Irishman.

00:33:03.520 --> 00:33:04.940
But they wouldn't let
me because they said

00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:05.980
it's not that good.

00:33:05.980 --> 00:33:06.400
You know?

00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:07.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:07.660 --> 00:33:07.798
BOBBY MCFERRIN: [IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:07.798 --> 00:33:08.505
But I tried.

00:33:08.505 --> 00:33:12.580
You know, the secret to
it, I think, is if you

00:33:12.580 --> 00:33:13.990
don't move your lips.

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:15.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:15.290 --> 00:33:15.580
MALE SPEAKER: [IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:15.580 --> 00:33:16.470
You just got to talk like
this [IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:16.470 --> 00:33:16.560
BOBBY MCFERRIN: [IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:17.730
You smile like that, right.

00:33:17.730 --> 00:33:18.610
And you start to talk.

00:33:18.610 --> 00:33:21.830
And that's the best way that
I can think of doing it.

00:33:21.830 --> 00:33:23.775
But it's not that
good, you know.

00:33:23.775 --> 00:33:24.920
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:24.920 --> 00:33:25.395
MALE SPEAKER: [IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:25.395 --> 00:33:27.720
When I get into me Irish accent,
I always have to start

00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:29.260
going tar, tar, tar, tar.

00:33:29.260 --> 00:33:29.500
BOBBY MCFERRIN: [IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:29.500 --> 00:33:30.060
Tar, tar,tar, tar.

00:33:30.060 --> 00:33:30.200
MALE SPEAKER: [IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:30.840
It just helps it out
a little bit.

00:33:30.840 --> 00:33:31.200
BOBBY MCFERRIN: [IRISH ACCENT]

00:33:31.200 --> 00:33:31.690
Ah, right.

00:33:31.690 --> 00:33:32.676
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:32.676 --> 00:33:35.470
MALE SPEAKER: Let's take
a question over here.

00:33:35.470 --> 00:33:36.570
AUDIENCE: I hope
you don't mind,

00:33:36.570 --> 00:33:37.870
but I have two questions.

00:33:37.870 --> 00:33:39.100
BOBBY MCFERRIN: What?!

00:33:39.100 --> 00:33:40.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:40.940 --> 00:33:41.840
AUDIENCE: Yeah, well.

00:33:41.840 --> 00:33:42.765
BOBBY MCFERRIN: OK.

00:33:42.765 --> 00:33:46.220
AUDIENCE: The first is I've seen
a number of musicians who

00:33:46.220 --> 00:33:48.800
sing as they play, which
I always thought

00:33:48.800 --> 00:33:49.940
was fascinating listening.

00:33:49.940 --> 00:33:50.660
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Sing
as they play.

00:33:50.660 --> 00:33:52.420
AUDIENCE: That they know their
instrument so well that

00:33:52.420 --> 00:33:57.080
they're singing along with their
playing, doing a solo.

00:33:57.080 --> 00:33:59.500
But you were playing while
you're singing.

00:33:59.500 --> 00:34:01.820
What instrument are you
playing on that mic?

00:34:01.820 --> 00:34:02.235
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Oh, this?

00:34:02.235 --> 00:34:04.760
You know, I played clarinet
when I was 10.

00:34:04.760 --> 00:34:08.889
And I have a feeling that this
was a carry-over of it.

00:34:08.889 --> 00:34:10.850
And it gives me a tactile
connection to the notes.

00:34:10.850 --> 00:34:11.435
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:34:11.435 --> 00:34:14.270
BOBBY MCFERRIN: [SINGING NOTES]

00:34:14.270 --> 00:34:15.570
You know?

00:34:15.570 --> 00:34:18.734
[SINGING NOTES]

00:34:18.734 --> 00:34:20.610
AUDIENCE: Well, it's
very consistent.

00:34:20.610 --> 00:34:22.514
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Thank you.

00:34:22.514 --> 00:34:24.429
AUDIENCE: I couldn't
tell what it was.

00:34:24.429 --> 00:34:25.790
It could be keyboards or--

00:34:25.790 --> 00:34:28.159
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Recorder.

00:34:28.159 --> 00:34:28.780
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:34:28.780 --> 00:34:33.100
Second question is, there was,
at least, two times this

00:34:33.100 --> 00:34:37.520
afternoon where you started
singing something, and after a

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:40.149
short time your keyboardist
started playing.

00:34:40.149 --> 00:34:40.800
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Yeah.

00:34:40.800 --> 00:34:41.900
AUDIENCE: So which is it?

00:34:41.900 --> 00:34:45.810
Are you starting in the correct
key because you've got

00:34:45.810 --> 00:34:46.650
perfect pitch?

00:34:46.650 --> 00:34:49.060
Or is he picking up the
key you're singing in?

00:34:49.060 --> 00:34:50.392
BOBBY MCFERRIN: He's picking up
the key that I'm singing.

00:34:50.392 --> 00:34:51.724
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:51.724 --> 00:34:52.659
BOBBY MCFERRIN: He's
got good ears.

00:34:52.659 --> 00:34:54.449
I have imperfect peach.

00:34:54.449 --> 00:34:54.704
Peach.

00:34:54.704 --> 00:34:55.150
MALE SPEAKER: Peaches?

00:34:55.150 --> 00:34:55.730
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Imperfect
peach.

00:34:55.730 --> 00:34:56.080
MALE SPEAKER: Imperfect
peaches?

00:34:56.080 --> 00:34:57.125
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Start
all over again.

00:34:57.125 --> 00:34:57.380
[SINGING]

00:34:57.380 --> 00:34:58.180
Start all over again.

00:34:58.180 --> 00:34:58.760
MALE SPEAKER: Rewind it.

00:34:58.760 --> 00:34:59.360
BOBBY MCFERRIN: [GIBBERISH]

00:34:59.360 --> 00:35:01.720
MALE SPEAKER: [GIBBERISH]

00:35:01.720 --> 00:35:04.415
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Imperfect
pitch.

00:35:04.415 --> 00:35:05.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:05.740 --> 00:35:07.580
MALE SPEAKER: I kept saying
peach in my head too.

00:35:07.580 --> 00:35:09.072
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I had
to think about that.

00:35:09.072 --> 00:35:09.937
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:35:09.937 --> 00:35:10.891
Over here.

00:35:10.891 --> 00:35:12.025
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:35:12.025 --> 00:35:14.620
I was wondering what you sound
like when your stuffed up, and

00:35:14.620 --> 00:35:16.750
if they're any sounds you can
make only when you're stuffed

00:35:16.750 --> 00:35:18.551
up that you wished you had?

00:35:18.551 --> 00:35:19.533
BOBBY MCFERRIN: [SINGING]

00:35:19.533 --> 00:35:21.550
Every little [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:21.550 --> 00:35:23.800
I have no idea what I
sound like though.

00:35:23.800 --> 00:35:24.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:24.700 --> 00:35:25.325
BOBBY MCFERRIN:
[STUFFED UP VOICE]

00:35:25.325 --> 00:35:30.140
I've never attempted to sing
anything when I'm on stage.

00:35:30.140 --> 00:35:31.680
I couldn't possibly do this.

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:32.170
I'd have to stop.

00:35:32.170 --> 00:35:32.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:32.660 --> 00:35:33.305
BOBBY MCFERRIN:
[STUFFED UP VOICE]

00:35:33.305 --> 00:35:34.000
But I could try.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:36.740
I could say, ladies and
gentleman, this is the best I

00:35:36.740 --> 00:35:37.930
can do for tonight.

00:35:37.930 --> 00:35:38.422
So I'll--

00:35:38.422 --> 00:35:39.406
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:39.406 --> 00:35:39.975
BOBBY MCFERRIN:
[STUFFED UP VOICE]

00:35:39.975 --> 00:35:42.220
--sing for about 30 minutes,
and then I'll have to stop.

00:35:42.220 --> 00:35:46.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:46.240 --> 00:35:46.870
AUDIENCE: Sounds about right.

00:35:46.870 --> 00:35:47.760
BOBBY MCFERRIN: The
answer is no.

00:35:47.760 --> 00:35:50.928
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:50.928 --> 00:35:52.860
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:35:52.860 --> 00:35:54.250
BOBBY MCFERRIN: You only have
one question, right?

00:35:54.250 --> 00:35:54.680
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:35:54.680 --> 00:35:55.942
BOBBY MCFERRIN: OK.

00:35:55.942 --> 00:35:58.930
MALE SPEAKER: What if you have
a drummer who keeps sneezing?

00:35:58.930 --> 00:36:00.062
LOUIS CATO: That happens
sometimes.

00:36:00.062 --> 00:36:01.745
MALE SPEAKER: You keep hitting
your head on the symbols?

00:36:01.745 --> 00:36:03.554
LOUIS CATO: That also happens.

00:36:03.554 --> 00:36:06.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:06.430 --> 00:36:07.410
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah?

00:36:07.410 --> 00:36:09.570
AUDIENCE: Hi, I want to
thank you for coming.

00:36:09.570 --> 00:36:11.590
I been listening to
you my whole life.

00:36:11.590 --> 00:36:13.290
My question is sort of random.

00:36:13.290 --> 00:36:16.820
It's about your multi-tonal
stuff that you do.

00:36:16.820 --> 00:36:17.310
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Multi tonal.

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:20.010
AUDIENCE: Like when you sing
harmony with yourself, I just

00:36:20.010 --> 00:36:21.435
have to say, it's bad-ass.

00:36:21.435 --> 00:36:23.290
It's so cool.

00:36:23.290 --> 00:36:28.180
And my question is how
did you discover that

00:36:28.180 --> 00:36:29.000
you could do that?

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:30.220
And what was your inspiration?

00:36:30.220 --> 00:36:32.380
And how can I do that?

00:36:32.380 --> 00:36:36.270
BOBBY MCFERRIN: OK,
let me tell you.

00:36:36.270 --> 00:36:39.000
I worked on my technique for
six years before I did my

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:41.540
first solo concert.

00:36:41.540 --> 00:36:43.820
I practiced, at least,
two hours a day.

00:36:43.820 --> 00:36:46.270
I took a tape recorder with
me everywhere I went.

00:36:46.270 --> 00:36:49.600
I purposely stayed away from
listening to other singers, on

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:52.100
purpose, because I'm very
impressionable.

00:36:52.100 --> 00:36:55.630
I was afraid that, if I found a
singer that I liked, I would

00:36:55.630 --> 00:36:58.300
latch on to their technique
and I'd never find myself.

00:36:58.300 --> 00:37:00.060
So I did a few things.

00:37:00.060 --> 00:37:01.640
I practiced for six years.

00:37:01.640 --> 00:37:05.290
I recognized, also, that what
I wanted to do involved more

00:37:05.290 --> 00:37:06.450
than singing notes.

00:37:06.450 --> 00:37:07.750
You had to sing character.

00:37:07.750 --> 00:37:09.800
You had sing color.

00:37:09.800 --> 00:37:11.740
You had to sing language.

00:37:11.740 --> 00:37:14.020
And so I started experimenting,
not only with

00:37:14.020 --> 00:37:15.660
the notes, but the texture
of the notes.

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:16.910
The approach of the notes.

00:37:16.910 --> 00:37:18.310
The dynamics of the notes.

00:37:18.310 --> 00:37:20.480
The weight of the notes.

00:37:20.480 --> 00:37:22.790
All that stuff had
to go into it.

00:37:22.790 --> 00:37:24.690
I could see myself
onstage alone.

00:37:24.690 --> 00:37:27.460
I couldn't hear anything
initially, but as I started to

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:31.810
sing a lot and practice a lot,
creating all kinds of

00:37:31.810 --> 00:37:34.500
exercises, and singing
intervals of tenths.

00:37:34.500 --> 00:37:36.200
Working on my chest voice
and my head voice.

00:37:36.200 --> 00:37:36.440
[SINGING]

00:37:36.440 --> 00:37:37.300
Chest.

00:37:37.300 --> 00:37:38.090
Head.

00:37:38.090 --> 00:37:38.508
Chest.

00:37:38.508 --> 00:37:39.344
Head.

00:37:39.344 --> 00:37:39.762
Chest.

00:37:39.762 --> 00:37:40.600
Head.

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:41.930
Things like that.

00:37:41.930 --> 00:37:45.140
So it just involved a
lot of singing over

00:37:45.140 --> 00:37:46.200
and over and over.

00:37:46.200 --> 00:37:47.240
Just all the time.

00:37:47.240 --> 00:37:48.460
Singing two records.

00:37:48.460 --> 00:37:49.950
You know, instrumentalists.

00:37:49.950 --> 00:37:51.740
Singing over changes.

00:37:51.740 --> 00:37:54.192
Changes meaning chord changes.

00:37:54.192 --> 00:37:55.990
That's it.

00:37:55.990 --> 00:37:57.800
Being a character.

00:37:57.800 --> 00:37:58.470
Having fun.

00:37:58.470 --> 00:38:00.800
Just giving yourself permission
to sing and sound

00:38:00.800 --> 00:38:02.065
like anything.

00:38:02.065 --> 00:38:03.845
You know?

00:38:03.845 --> 00:38:06.380
AUDIENCE: And what about the
two notes at once thing?

00:38:06.380 --> 00:38:10.490
BOBBY MCFERRIN:
[SINGING A NOTE SOUND]

00:38:10.490 --> 00:38:13.890
That's buzzing your lips for
one tone and then humming.

00:38:13.890 --> 00:38:21.280
[SINGING NOTE SOUND]

00:38:21.280 --> 00:38:22.460
That's it, sort of.

00:38:22.460 --> 00:38:23.445
It's no secret.

00:38:23.445 --> 00:38:23.700
AUDIENCE: So cool.

00:38:23.700 --> 00:38:24.966
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:24.966 --> 00:38:26.635
AUDIENCE: You can hum
and whistle too.

00:38:26.635 --> 00:38:27.795
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I can what?

00:38:27.795 --> 00:38:28.345
AUDIENCE: Hum and whistle.

00:38:28.345 --> 00:38:29.410
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Hum
and whistle.

00:38:29.410 --> 00:38:30.650
I wish I could come
hum and whistle.

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:31.930
I can't.

00:38:31.930 --> 00:38:37.980
I know someone who can whistle
and hum in counterpoint.

00:38:37.980 --> 00:38:42.350
And she has a sister who
can do the same thing.

00:38:42.350 --> 00:38:47.020
So they do four part
Bach things.

00:38:47.020 --> 00:38:48.830
It's pretty amazing.

00:38:48.830 --> 00:38:50.600
And her name is Irene
Goodnight.

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:50.980
[SINGING]

00:38:50.980 --> 00:38:53.390
Goodnight Irene.

00:38:53.390 --> 00:38:55.520
Goodnight Irene.

00:38:55.520 --> 00:38:56.420
Do, do, dee.

00:38:56.420 --> 00:38:57.890
Yes?

00:38:57.890 --> 00:38:59.160
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:38:59.160 --> 00:39:01.980
So touching back, talking about
when you were starting

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:06.180
to sing, you had a band when
you where 14, right?

00:39:06.180 --> 00:39:07.870
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I lived
in Los Angeles.

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:11.370
I had a band called The
Fascinations when I was 14.

00:39:11.370 --> 00:39:13.120
I've been a working musician
since I was 14.

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:15.130
I'm 63, so what is that?

00:39:15.130 --> 00:39:18.970
Is that 50 years, almost 50
years, working as a musician.

00:39:18.970 --> 00:39:21.470
And I had a band called
The Fascinations.

00:39:21.470 --> 00:39:23.370
We played the top 40 stuff
that was on the

00:39:23.370 --> 00:39:24.220
radio at the time.

00:39:24.220 --> 00:39:26.730
MALE SPEAKER: So you where
piano at that point.

00:39:26.730 --> 00:39:27.340
Pianist, right?

00:39:27.340 --> 00:39:28.580
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I was a
piano player, right.

00:39:28.580 --> 00:39:30.610
MALE SPEAKER: So what
was in the band?

00:39:30.610 --> 00:39:32.520
You guys had the piano.

00:39:32.520 --> 00:39:36.030
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Piano, guitar,
lead guitar, rhythm guitar,

00:39:36.030 --> 00:39:39.480
drums, and lead singer.

00:39:39.480 --> 00:39:40.620
MALE SPEAKER: That's
wonderful.

00:39:40.620 --> 00:39:41.570
OK, question over here.

00:39:41.570 --> 00:39:42.145
Yeah?

