[LAUGHTER]

00:43:39.282 --> 00:43:40.532
MALE SPEAKER: Question please.

00:43:43.126 --> 00:43:45.630
AUDIENCE: It is such a treat
to hear you in person.

00:43:45.630 --> 00:43:47.340
Thank you so much for coming.

00:43:47.340 --> 00:43:50.320
I just want to tell you that
your album, "Circle Songs," is

00:43:50.320 --> 00:43:53.080
something that, for years, I've
always turned to if I

00:43:53.080 --> 00:43:54.810
needed some spiritual
uplifting.

00:43:54.810 --> 00:43:55.180
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Yeah, thanks.

00:43:55.180 --> 00:43:58.010
AUDIENCE: So I want to thank
you, in person, for that one.

00:43:58.010 --> 00:43:59.140
BOBBY MCFERRIN: You're
very welcome.

00:43:59.140 --> 00:44:01.900
AUDIENCE: Also, my hometown
is Saint Paul, Minnesota.

00:44:01.900 --> 00:44:02.485
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Sure.

00:44:02.485 --> 00:44:05.110
AUDIENCE: And I was wondering
how you enjoyed working there

00:44:05.110 --> 00:44:06.090
when you were working
with them?

00:44:06.090 --> 00:44:08.670
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I loved it
because, when they hired me, I

00:44:08.670 --> 00:44:11.410
was a brand new conductor.

00:44:11.410 --> 00:44:14.610
I had no clue what to
do with the Saint

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:15.155
Paul Chamber Orchestra.

00:44:15.155 --> 00:44:17.160
I didn't know how to rehearse.

00:44:17.160 --> 00:44:19.910
I hadn't settled on any kind
of stick technique, of any

00:44:19.910 --> 00:44:22.030
kind, to lead the orchestra.

00:44:22.030 --> 00:44:23.790
Hand technique.

00:44:23.790 --> 00:44:26.050
So they were very, very
patient with me.

00:44:26.050 --> 00:44:28.230
They hired me with no
understanding of what they

00:44:28.230 --> 00:44:29.510
were getting into.

00:44:29.510 --> 00:44:32.685
And I worked with them for six
seasons or seven seasons, one

00:44:32.685 --> 00:44:35.140
or the other, and they were
my first teachers.

00:44:35.140 --> 00:44:37.620
And this is a revelation.

00:44:37.620 --> 00:44:40.590
I'm spending a lot of time
trying to be a conductor.

00:44:40.590 --> 00:44:43.050
So I figured you had to
talk like a conductor.

00:44:43.050 --> 00:44:44.870
Clarinets on bar 92.

00:44:44.870 --> 00:44:47.580
A little bit more diminuendo
at the end of the phrase.

00:44:47.580 --> 00:44:49.115
Blah, blah, blah.

00:44:49.115 --> 00:44:52.290
And finally, I just
wasn't getting it.

00:44:52.290 --> 00:44:56.375
And, dadgum it, the woodwind
section comes to me one day in

00:44:56.375 --> 00:44:56.845
my dresser room.

00:44:56.845 --> 00:45:02.558
And they said, why don't
you just sing to us?

00:45:02.558 --> 00:45:03.980
Duh, you know?

00:45:03.980 --> 00:45:05.970
What a revelation that was.

00:45:05.970 --> 00:45:08.420
And so from then on, when I
wanted something from a

00:45:08.420 --> 00:45:11.290
particular section of the
orchestra, I'd sing it.

00:45:11.290 --> 00:45:13.050
And that would give them
all the information.

00:45:13.050 --> 00:45:15.110
The flexibility of the phrase.

00:45:15.110 --> 00:45:16.640
The dynamics of the phrase.

00:45:16.640 --> 00:45:18.610
How long the phrase went.

00:45:18.610 --> 00:45:19.760
How long it lasted.

00:45:19.760 --> 00:45:21.460
And that was a revelation
for me.

00:45:21.460 --> 00:45:22.940
And I don't know why
didn't think of it.

00:45:22.940 --> 00:45:24.500
I mean, I'm a singer,
after all.

00:45:24.500 --> 00:45:28.300
Instead of trying to sound very
conductorial they said,

00:45:28.300 --> 00:45:28.950
just sing to us.

00:45:28.950 --> 00:45:29.960
We'll get it.

00:45:29.960 --> 00:45:31.502
But just sing.

00:45:31.502 --> 00:45:32.004
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:45:32.004 --> 00:45:32.050
That's beautiful.

00:45:32.050 --> 00:45:32.500
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I loved it.

00:45:32.500 --> 00:45:34.681
I had a great time.

00:45:34.681 --> 00:45:35.850
[SINGING SHORT TUNE]

00:45:35.850 --> 00:45:39.270
AUDIENCE: I have a little bit
more of a technical question.

00:45:39.270 --> 00:45:46.820
I am very impressed with the
effects you do in your voice.

00:45:46.820 --> 00:45:50.380
But I can't help but notice that
I believe there's some

00:45:50.380 --> 00:45:53.340
reverb going on or some delay.

00:45:53.340 --> 00:45:55.750
Is this just my mind playing
tricks on me?

00:45:55.750 --> 00:45:56.720
BOBBY MCFERRIN: No,
it depends.

00:45:56.720 --> 00:45:58.180
Sometimes there's
a little delay,

00:45:58.180 --> 00:46:00.220
depending on what I'm doing.

00:46:00.220 --> 00:46:02.270
Ive been working with
the sound man, Danny

00:46:02.270 --> 00:46:04.350
Vicari for 25 years.

00:46:04.350 --> 00:46:06.180
He knows me really,
really well.

00:46:06.180 --> 00:46:10.660
So he'll just, maybe, put a
little delay on something.

00:46:10.660 --> 00:46:12.170
No, you're not hearing
anything.

00:46:12.170 --> 00:46:13.060
You're not hearing anything.

00:46:13.060 --> 00:46:13.930
You're not hearing anything.

00:46:13.930 --> 00:46:15.670
You're not hearing anything.

00:46:15.670 --> 00:46:16.120
You know.

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:16.570
You know.

00:46:16.570 --> 00:46:17.446
You know.

00:46:17.446 --> 00:46:18.300
You know.

00:46:18.300 --> 00:46:19.120
AUDIENCE: I couldn't tell.

00:46:19.120 --> 00:46:19.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:19.780 --> 00:46:24.560
AUDIENCE: So in that case, I'll
grab a second question.

00:46:24.560 --> 00:46:27.860
So I always felt that voice is
a very natural kind of thing.

00:46:27.860 --> 00:46:29.200
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Yeah.

00:46:29.200 --> 00:46:31.180
AUDIENCE: And at least right
now, ever since '70s and '80s

00:46:31.180 --> 00:46:39.190
delays, going digital, I feel
that they mess up a lot of it.

00:46:39.190 --> 00:46:40.450
They take a lot of neutrality.

00:46:40.450 --> 00:46:42.660
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Yeah,
auto-tune.

00:46:42.660 --> 00:46:43.740
Boo.

00:46:43.740 --> 00:46:46.160
AUDIENCE: Yeah, what's
your opinion on that?

00:46:46.160 --> 00:46:48.140
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I don't
like a lot of it.

00:46:48.140 --> 00:46:50.510
I don't like manipulating
of the voices a lot.

00:46:50.510 --> 00:46:57.140
I think it's an excuse for
not being talented.

00:46:57.140 --> 00:46:59.780
A lot of singers rely
on it to help them

00:46:59.780 --> 00:47:01.130
sing in tune or whatever.

00:47:01.130 --> 00:47:03.490
I don't really want
to get into it.

00:47:03.490 --> 00:47:06.330
It's a waste of time for me.

00:47:06.330 --> 00:47:07.370
I don't explore it.

00:47:07.370 --> 00:47:11.600
I knew at the beginning that I
didn't want to use any effects

00:47:11.600 --> 00:47:14.890
doing solo concerts because I
was afraid that if I got in

00:47:14.890 --> 00:47:17.990
trouble doing an improv, and
it wasn't working, that I'd

00:47:17.990 --> 00:47:23.250
bail myself out by clicking a
switch and bringing up some

00:47:23.250 --> 00:47:24.390
kind of an effect.

00:47:24.390 --> 00:47:26.760
I didn't want to do that, so
I stayed away from it.

00:47:26.760 --> 00:47:27.840
I like to do everything
organically.

00:47:27.840 --> 00:47:29.390
MALE SPEAKER: Have you ever got
in trouble in a concert?

00:47:29.390 --> 00:47:31.066
BOBBY MCFERRIN: No.

00:47:31.066 --> 00:47:32.560
MALE SPEAKER: Then
you're all set.

00:47:32.560 --> 00:47:33.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:33.250 --> 00:47:34.390
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Well, you
know, it's improv.

00:47:34.390 --> 00:47:37.345
If you mess up, you don't really
mess up in improv.

00:47:37.345 --> 00:47:38.850
MALE SPEAKER: Just do it again,
and it sounds like you

00:47:38.850 --> 00:47:39.490
did it on purpose.

00:47:39.490 --> 00:47:40.070
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Do it again.

00:47:40.070 --> 00:47:41.140
Sounds like you did
it on purpose.

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:41.450
MALE SPEAKER: Right.

00:47:41.450 --> 00:47:44.740
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Or maybe what
you messed up took you

00:47:44.740 --> 00:47:46.470
someplace that you hadn't
intended on going.

00:47:46.470 --> 00:47:48.893
And you find something that you
would not have found if

00:47:48.893 --> 00:47:51.755
you had stuck with your
original intent.

00:47:51.755 --> 00:47:53.520
MALE SPEAKER: So how long have
you been playing with these

00:47:53.520 --> 00:47:55.400
two fellows?

00:47:55.400 --> 00:47:56.920
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Well, Gil and I
have been playing together,

00:47:56.920 --> 00:47:58.670
off and on, for a few years.

00:47:58.670 --> 00:48:00.360
Maybe, five or six or
something like that.

00:48:00.360 --> 00:48:01.800
Maybe even longer.

00:48:01.800 --> 00:48:02.490
Seven or eight.

00:48:02.490 --> 00:48:03.230
Whatever.

00:48:03.230 --> 00:48:07.290
And Louis since, maybe, April.

00:48:07.290 --> 00:48:08.290
LOUIS CATO: End of
March, yeah.

00:48:08.290 --> 00:48:08.940
BOBBY MCFERRIN: End of March.

00:48:08.940 --> 00:48:10.190
Beginning of April.

00:48:12.980 --> 00:48:14.330
MALE SPEAKER: You're
very tight.

00:48:14.330 --> 00:48:15.780
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Yeah, I should
also say that there's three

00:48:15.780 --> 00:48:20.320
other members of the band who
weren't here today because I

00:48:20.320 --> 00:48:20.910
don't know.

00:48:20.910 --> 00:48:22.710
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:22.710 --> 00:48:24.630
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I guess they
thought there wasn't enough

00:48:24.630 --> 00:48:26.210
space on stage for everyone.

