And then the other guy plays
acoustic and electric guitar.

00:48:39.390 --> 00:48:42.710
And then with Cato playing
guitar, sometimes we have

00:48:42.710 --> 00:48:45.050
three guitars playing.

00:48:45.050 --> 00:48:49.320
So including myself, it's
a six member band.

00:48:49.320 --> 00:48:50.440
Six piece band.

00:48:50.440 --> 00:48:50.650
MALE SPEAKER: Wow.

00:48:50.650 --> 00:48:54.860
So how much time do you spend
rehearsing improvisation?

00:48:54.860 --> 00:48:55.580
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Now?

00:48:55.580 --> 00:48:56.300
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:48:56.300 --> 00:48:58.190
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Well,
every day.

00:48:58.190 --> 00:49:00.690
I don't know how much time,
but I sing every day.

00:49:00.690 --> 00:49:01.490
MALE SPEAKER: Right.

00:49:01.490 --> 00:49:02.160
I mean, not you.

00:49:02.160 --> 00:49:04.500
But I mean as a whole band
because you guys have to know.

00:49:04.500 --> 00:49:06.290
You start learning each
other, and you

00:49:06.290 --> 00:49:06.620
learn about each other.

00:49:06.620 --> 00:49:07.680
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Yeah, but
they have great ears.

00:49:07.680 --> 00:49:11.440
If I take off and start to
improvise and come out with

00:49:11.440 --> 00:49:16.090
some really off the wall place
that I want to go, they pick

00:49:16.090 --> 00:49:17.020
it up really quickly.

00:49:17.020 --> 00:49:19.095
MALE SPEAKER: Was that part
of the audition process?

00:49:19.095 --> 00:49:20.160
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Probably.

00:49:20.160 --> 00:49:21.045
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah?

00:49:21.045 --> 00:49:21.920
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Yeah.

00:49:21.920 --> 00:49:23.110
MALE SPEAKER: Just give them a
beat, and see if they can make

00:49:23.110 --> 00:49:23.710
it sound good?

00:49:23.710 --> 00:49:24.865
BOBBY MCFERRIN: Yeah, sure.

00:49:24.865 --> 00:49:26.400
MALE SPEAKER: That's not bad.

00:49:26.400 --> 00:49:27.255
Question.

00:49:27.255 --> 00:49:28.580
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:49:28.580 --> 00:49:29.880
This might be a bit of
a broad question.

00:49:29.880 --> 00:49:31.950
But I was wondering if you could
tell us about a time

00:49:31.950 --> 00:49:34.580
when there was some vocal effect
that really gave you

00:49:34.580 --> 00:49:38.860
difficulty in learning how to do
it and, ultimately, getting

00:49:38.860 --> 00:49:40.475
it the way you wanted
it to sound.

00:49:40.475 --> 00:49:46.450
BOBBY MCFERRIN: No, my approach
was never to listen

00:49:46.450 --> 00:49:49.200
to a sound and try
to imitate it.

00:49:49.200 --> 00:49:50.780
I never went for that.

00:49:50.780 --> 00:49:52.090
AUDIENCE: You just made them
all up from scratch.

00:49:52.090 --> 00:49:55.650
BOBBY MCFERRIN: I would just
make them all up on the spot.

00:49:55.650 --> 00:49:58.490
I'd give myself different
exercises to play.

00:49:58.490 --> 00:50:00.710
Like, say, for two
minutes, I'm only

00:50:00.710 --> 00:50:03.020
going to sing one note.

00:50:03.020 --> 00:50:04.550
So how many different
ways can I sing it?

00:50:04.550 --> 00:50:06.250
Things like that.

00:50:06.250 --> 00:50:11.590
I would give myself all kinds of
musical challenges to face.

00:50:11.590 --> 00:50:11.970
That's all.

00:50:11.970 --> 00:50:14.290
But I never would listen
to a sound.

00:50:14.290 --> 00:50:17.200
A lot of people say, well, you
sound just like a trumpet.

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:19.120
Well, I never studied
the trumpet.

00:50:19.120 --> 00:50:20.890
I never listened to the trumpet
and tried to emulate

00:50:20.890 --> 00:50:22.660
it or imitate it.

00:50:22.660 --> 00:50:24.090
Imitate it.

00:50:24.090 --> 00:50:25.080
I never tried to do that.

00:50:25.080 --> 00:50:28.020
It was always just trying,
getting things out of me or

00:50:28.020 --> 00:50:29.725
from the inside out.

00:50:29.725 --> 00:50:31.520
AUDIENCE: It sounds like there's
all sorts of sound

00:50:31.520 --> 00:50:32.420
